NG // Exclude from production build void test_display_text_draw(struct font_freetype_text *text, struct graphics_priv *gr, struct graphics_gc_priv *fg, struct graphics_gc_priv *bg, int color, struct point *p) { display_text_draw(text, gr, fg, bg, color, p); } #endif ``` In your testing framework or build configurations, define `TESTING` to include the wrapper. Ensure `TESTING` is not defined in production builds to avoid exposing test-only code. # 3. Use Friend Test Classes (C++ Only) If you\'re working with C++, you can leverage friendship and testing frameworks to access `static` functions. However, because `display_text_draw` is a C-style function, this approach might not fit well without wrapping the functionality in a class, which could be more effort than it\'s worth if you\'re not already using C++ extensively. # 4. Link Against the Object File Directly (Brittle) Another approach, more of a hack, is to include the `.o` object file or equivalent directly in your test suite\'s build script. This is highly dependent on your build system and is generally not recommended because it\'s brittle and complicates the build process. ```makefile # Example Makefile snippet test_suite: test_suite.o display_text_draw.o (CC) -o @ ^ ``` This method requires direct access to the compiled object file and tightly couples your test suite to the implementation details. # Choosing an Approach The best approach depends on your project\'s requirements, the build system you\'re using, and how you structure your tests. The test wrapper method offers a good balance between accessibility for testing and maintaining the benefits of `static` linkage. Always weigh the benefits of testing accessibility against the potential risks of changing the visibility and linkage of internal functions."},{"instruction":"if struct graphics_gc_priv *bg; how can we provide values to bg to execute statements in condition if(bg){ }","output":"If you have a structure `struct graphics_gc_priv *bg;` and you wan